{"title_page": "Monik Charette", "text_new": "{{short description|French Canadian linguist and phonologist}}{{Infobox academic|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1949|05|29|df=yes}}|nationality=Canadian|discipline=Linguist|sub_discipline=[[Phonology]]|alma_mater={{Plainlist|\n* [[Universit\u00e9 du Qu\u00e9bec \u00e0 Montr\u00e9al]] {{Small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}\n* [[McGill University]] {{Small|([[Master of Arts|MA]], ([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])}}\n}}|workplaces=[[SOAS University of London]]|known_for=[[Government phonology]]}}\n\n'''Monik Charette''' (born 29 May 1949) is a French Canadian [[Linguistics|linguist]] and [[Phonology|phonologist]] who taught at the [[University of London]], in the United Kingdom. She specializes in [[phonology]], [[morphophonology]], [[Stress (linguistics)|stress systems]], [[vowel harmony]], [[syllable|syllabic structure]] and word-structure, focusing on [[Altaic languages]], [[Turkish language|Turkish]], and [[French language|French]].\n\n== Education and career ==\nCharette earned her [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] from [[Universit\u00e9 du Qu\u00e9bec \u00e0 Montr\u00e9al]] (UQAM), and her [[Master of Arts|MA]] and [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] from [[McGill University]], graduating in 1988. By 1989 she was working as a Training Fellow in Linguistics at the University of London [[SOAS University of London|School of Oriental and African Studies]]; by 2010 she was a [[Reader (academic rank)|reader]] in linguistics there, and later became a [[senior lecturer]], teaching courses on phonology at undergraduate and postgraduate levels. She was also associate dean for postgraduate matters at the Faculty of Languages and Cultures.\n\nCharette retired and moved back to Canada in 2019.\n\n== Research ==\nCharette is one of the founders and first proponents of [[Government phonology|Government Phonology]], the phonological adaptation of [[Government and binding theory|Government and Binding Theory]] in [[syntax]], with work done on vowel-zero alternation in French, on government-licensing, on [[Head (linguistics)|headedness]] in element theory, on empty and pseudo-empty categories, on Turkish word-structure, among many others. Government Phonology she contributed the concepts of government-licensing<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Stong-Jensen |first1=Margaret |title=Review of Conditions on Phonological Government by Monik Charette |journal=Phonology |date=1993 |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=347\u2013357}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheer |first1=Tobias |title=A lateral theory of phonology. Vol 1: What is CVCV, and why should it be? |date=2004 |publisher=Mouton de Gruyter |location=Berlin |pages=137\u2013138.}}</ref> and licensing constraints;<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Scheer |first1=Tobias |last2=Kula |first2=Nancy C. |title=Government Phonology: Element theory, conceptual issues and introduction |journal=The Routledge Handbook of Phonological Theory |date=2018 |page=233}}</ref> in 1989 she was the first to propose a phonological version of the [[Minimalist program|Minimality Condition]].\n\nWith Asli G\u00f6kse, Charette conducted research on licensing constraints (LC's);<ref>[https://archipel.uqam.ca/6535/1/D2647.pdf \"The phonology of empty categories\"]. Thesis by Paul John at the Universit\u00e9 du Qu\u00e9bec \u00e0 Montr\u00e9al, April 2014</ref><ref>Edmund Gussmann, [http://tscheer.free.fr/papers/Scheer%2010%20-%20Review%20of%20Gussmann%20(2007)%20The%20Phonology%20of%20Polish.pdf ''The Phonology of Polish''], Oxford University Press 2007, pages 117 and 128</ref> later research on LC's refers to their work as the \"Charette-G\u00f6ksel Hypothesis\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kaye |first1=Jonathan |authorlink1=Jonathan_Kaye |editor1-last=Dziubalska-Kolaczyk |editor1-first=Katarzyna |title=Constraints and Preferences |date=2001 |publisher=Mouton de Gruyter |location=Berlin & New York |page=256 |chapter=Working with licensing constraints}}</ref> Together with [[Jonathan Kaye (linguist)|Jonathan Kaye]], she led the research at [[SOAS University of London|SOAS, London]], aimed at reducing the number of elements in Element Theory, concluding in the emergence of the so-called Revised Theory of Elements.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Scheer |first1=Tobias |last2=Kula |first2=Nancy C. |title=Government Phonology: Element theory, conceptual issues and introduction |journal=The Routledge Handbook of Phonological Theory |date=2018 |page=226}}</ref>\n\nCharette's most cited work is her monograph from 1991, ''Conditions on Phonological Government'', published by [[Cambridge University Press]], which is the first extended study written within the framework of phonological government.<ref>''[https://books.google.com/books?id=bTGFAAAAIAAJ Lingua]''. 1995. p. 28.</ref> In her analysis of French, she contributed to the general understanding of the relation between skeletal positions and higher prosodic structure in the form of her \"pointless onsets\" in [[Aspirated h|h-aspir\u00e9]] words.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Szigetv\u00e1ri |first1=P\u00e9ter |title=Skeleton |journal=Blackwell Companion to Phonology |date=2011 |page=1273}}</ref> She participated in the preparations of the [[festschrift]] for Jonathan Kaye, ''Living on the Edge'', eventually edited by Stefan Ploch alone and published in 2003.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ploch |first1=Stefan |title=Living on the edge: 28 papers in honour of Jonathan Kaye |date=2003 |publisher=M. de Gruyter |location=Berlin; New York |page=v}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Charette spoke at the Ninth Manchester Phonology Meeting in the session ''Phonology and syntax - the same or different?'', where she presented the Government Phonology perspective. In 2009, she co-edited, with [[Peter Austin (linguist)|Peter K. Austin]], Oliver Bond, David Nathan and Peter Sells, the volume ''Proceedings of Conference on Language Documentation and Linguistic Theory 2'', London: SOAS. Her contributions to the understanding of the [[syllable]] in phonological theory, of Turkish vowel harmony and of [[schwa]] in French are acknowledged in handbooks and companions to phonology.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Goldsmith |first1=John |last2=Riggle |first2=Jason |last3=Yu |first3=Alan C. L. |title=The handbook of phonological theory |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell |isbn=9781405157681 |edition=2nd}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Kula |first1=Nancy C. |last2=Botma |first2=Bert |last3=Nasukawa |first3=Kuniya |title=Continuum companion to phonology |date=2011 |publisher=Continuum International Pub. Group |isbn=9780826434234}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=van Oostendorp |first1=Marc |last2=Ewen |first2=Colin |last3=Hume |first3=Elizabeth |last4=Rice |first4=Keren |title=The Blackwell companion to phonology |date=2011 |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell |isbn=9781405184236}}</ref>\n\n== Major publications ==\n* 1989 \"The Minimality Condition in Phonology\". ''Journal of Linguistics'' 25.1: 159-187. \n* 1990 \"Licence to govern\". ''Phonology'' 7: 233-253. \n* 1991 ''Conditions on Phonological Government''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.<ref>''[https://books.google.com/books?id=zEpZAAAAMAAJ Word]''. S.F. Vanni; 1999. p. 119.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=KqcoAQAAIAAJ \"Review of Conditions on Phonological Government\"]. by Mike Maxwell, in ''Notes on Linguistics''. Issues 56-63. Summer Institute of Linguistics; 1992. p. 62\u201364.</ref>\n* 1992 \"Mongolian and Polish meet Government Licensing\". ''SOAS Working Papers in Linguistics and Phonetics'' 2: 275-291. \n* 1994 \"Vowel Harmony and Switching in Turkic languages\". ''SOAS Working Papers in Linguistics and Phonetics'' 4: 31-52. Also in Kardela, Henryk, Bogdan Szymanek (eds.), ''A Festschrift for Edmund Gussmann'', 29-56. Lublin 1996: University Press of the Catholic University of Lublin.\n* 1996 \"Licensing constraints and vowel harmony in Turkic languages\". ''SOAS Working Papers in Linguistics and Phonetics'' 6: 1-25. Also in Cyran, Eugeniusz (ed.), ''Structure and Interpretation. Studies in Phonology'', 65-88. Lublin 1998: Folium.\n* 1998 \"Empty and pseudo-empty categories\". ''SOAS Working Papers in Linguistics and Phonetics'' 8: 167-176.\n* 2000 \"When p-licensing fails: the final high vowels of Turkish\". ''SOAS Working Papers in Linguistics'': 3-18.\n* 2003 \"Empty and pseudo-empty categories\". In ''Living on the Edge. 28 papers in honour of Jonathan Kaye'', Stefan Ploch (ed.), 465-479. Berlin, New York: Mouton de Gruyter.\n* 2004 \"Defining the structure of Turkish words\". ''SOAS Working Papers in Linguistics'' 13: 49-79.\n* 2006 \"The end of the (Turkish) word\". ''SOAS Working Papers in Linguistics'' 14: 23-40.\n* 2008 \"The vital role of the trochaic foot in explaining Turkish word endings\". ''Lingua'' 118.1: 46-65.\n* 2018 \"The internal TR clusters of Acadian French: a hint from schwa\". In: Lindsey, Geoff and Nevins, Andrew, (eds.), ''Sonic Signatures''. Amsterdam: John Benjamins.\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://scholar.google.co.in/scholar?q=Monik+Charette&hl=en Google Scholar report]\n*{{cite book |last1=Charette |first1=Monik |title=Some constraints on governing relations in phonology |date=1988 |publisher=McGill University |url=http://digitool.library.mcgill.ca/R/?func=dbin-jump-full&object_id=75950 |accessdate=12 August 2019}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Charette, Monik}}\n[[Category:Linguists from Canada]]\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Universit\u00e9 du Qu\u00e9bec \u00e0 Montr\u00e9al alumni]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Academics of SOAS University of London]]\n[[Category:Phonologists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French Canadian linguist and phonologist}}{{Infobox academic|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1949|05|29|df=yes}}|nationality=Canadian|discipline=Linguist|sub_discipline=[[Phonology]]|alma_mater={{Plainlist|\n* [[Universit\u00e9 du Qu\u00e9bec \u00e0 Montr\u00e9al]] {{Small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}\n* [[McGill University]] {{Small|([[Master of Arts|MA]], ([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])}}\n}}|workplaces=[[SOAS University of London]]|known_for=[[Government phonology]]}}\n\n'''Monik Charette''' (born 29 May 1949) is a French Canadian [[Linguistics|linguist]] and [[Phonology|phonologist]] who taught at the [[University of London]], in the United Kingdom. She specializes in [[phonology]], [[morphophonology]], [[Stress (linguistics)|stress systems]], [[vowel harmony]], [[syllable|syllabic structure]] and word-structure, focusing on [[Altaic languages]], [[Turkish language|Turkish]], and [[French language|French]].\n\n== Education and career ==\nCharette earned her [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] from [[Universit\u00e9 du Qu\u00e9bec \u00e0 Montr\u00e9al]] (UQAM), and her [[Master of Arts|MA]] and [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] from [[McGill University]], graduating in 1988. By 1989 she was working as a Training Fellow in Linguistics at the University of London [[SOAS University of London|School of Oriental and African Studies]]; by 2010 she was a [[Reader (academic rank)|reader]] in linguistics there, and later became a [[senior lecturer]], teaching courses on phonology at undergraduate and postgraduate levels. She was also associate dean for postgraduate matters at the Faculty of Languages and Cultures. \n\nCharette retired and moved back to Canada in 2019.\n\n== Research ==\nCharette is one of the founders and first proponents of [[Government phonology|Government Phonology]], the phonological adaptation of [[Government_and_binding_theory|Government and Binding Theory]] in [[syntax]], with work done on vowel-zero alternation in French, on government-licensing, on [[Head (linguistics)|headedness]] in element theory, on empty and pseudo-empty categories, on Turkish word-structure, among many others. Government Phonology she contributed the concepts of government-licensing<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Stong-Jensen |first1=Margaret |title=Review of Conditions on Phonological Government by Monik Charette |journal=Phonology |date=1993 |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=347-357}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheer |first1=Tobias |title=A lateral theory of phonology. Vol 1: What is CVCV, and why should it be? |date=2004 |publisher=Mouton de Gruyter |location=Berlin |pages=137-138.}}</ref> and licensing constraints;<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Scheer |first1=Tobias |last2=Kula |first2=Nancy C. |title=Government Phonology: Element theory, conceptual issues and introduction |journal=The Routledge Handbook of Phonological Theory |date=2018 |page=233}}</ref> in 1989 she was the first to propose a phonological version of the [[Minimalist_program|Minimality Condition]]. \n\nWith Asli G\u00f6kse, Charette conducted research on licensing constraints (LC's);<ref>[https://archipel.uqam.ca/6535/1/D2647.pdf \"The phonology of empty categories\"]. Thesis by Paul John at the Universit\u00e9 du Qu\u00e9bec \u00e0 Montr\u00e9al, April 2014</ref><ref>Edmund Gussmann, [http://tscheer.free.fr/papers/Scheer%2010%20-%20Review%20of%20Gussmann%20(2007)%20The%20Phonology%20of%20Polish.pdf ''The Phonology of Polish''], Oxford University Press 2007, pages 117 and 128 </ref> later research on LC's refers to their work as the \"Charette-G\u00f6ksel Hypothesis\".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kaye |first1=Jonathan |authorlink1=Jonathan_Kaye |editor1-last=Dziubalska-Kolaczyk |editor1-first=Katarzyna |title=Constraints and Preferences |date=2001 |publisher=Mouton de Gruyter |location=Berlin & New York |page=256 |chapter=Working with licensing constraints}}</ref> Together with [[Jonathan_Kaye_(linguist)|Jonathan Kaye]], she led the research at [[SOAS University of London|SOAS, London]], aimed at reducing the number of elements in Element Theory, concluding in the emergence of the so-called Revised Theory of Elements.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Scheer |first1=Tobias |last2=Kula |first2=Nancy C. |title=Government Phonology: Element theory, conceptual issues and introduction |journal=The Routledge Handbook of Phonological Theory |date=2018 |page=226}}</ref>\n\nCharette's most cited work is her monograph from 1991, ''Conditions on Phonological Government'', published by [[Cambridge University Press]], which is the first extended study written within the framework of phonological government.<ref>''[https://books.google.com/books?id=bTGFAAAAIAAJ Lingua]''. 1995. p. 28.</ref> In her analysis of French, she contributed to the general understanding of the relation between skeletal positions and higher prosodic structure in the form of her \"pointless onsets\" in [[Aspirated h|h-aspir\u00e9]] words.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Szigetv\u00e1ri |first1=P\u00e9ter |title=Skeleton |journal=Blackwell Companion to Phonology |date=2011 |page=1273}}</ref> She participated in the preparations of the [[festschrift]] for Jonathan Kaye, ''Living on the Edge'', eventually edited by Stefan Ploch alone and published in 2003.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ploch |first1=Stefan |title=Living on the edge: 28 papers in honour of Jonathan Kaye |date=2003 |publisher=M. de Gruyter |location=Berlin; New York |page=v}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Charette spoke at the Ninth Manchester Phonology Meeting in the session ''Phonology and syntax - the same or different?'', where she presented the Government Phonology perspective. In 2009, she co-edited, with [[Peter Austin (linguist)|Peter K. Austin]], Oliver Bond, David Nathan and Peter Sells, the volume ''Proceedings of Conference on Language Documentation and Linguistic Theory 2'', London: SOAS. Her contributions to the understanding of the [[syllable]] in phonological theory, of Turkish vowel harmony and of [[schwa]] in French are acknowledged in handbooks and companions to phonology.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Goldsmith |first1=John |last2=Riggle |first2=Jason |last3=Yu |