u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "#REDIRECT [[List of rural localities in Vologda Oblast#Belozersky District]]{{rcat shell|{{R to list entry}}}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "WP:STUB", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sidorovo,_Belozersky_District,_Vologda_Oblast"}
{"title_page": "Gold Coast Influenza Epidemic", "text_new": "An influenza epidemic in [[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]] (Modern day Ghana) in 1918-1919 killed 100,000 people or more in six months.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Patterson|first=K. David|date=October 1983|title=The Influenza Epidemic of 1918\u201319 in the Gold Coast1|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-african-history/article/influenza-epidemic-of-191819-in-the-gold-coast1/93EFCA1CDC9FC2735A289728934E628C|journal=The Journal of African History|language=en|volume=24|issue=4|pages=485\u2013502|doi=10.1017/S0021853700028012|issn=1469-5138}}</ref> Globally, 20 million people died from the outbreak in 1918.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.blakkpepper.com/2016/11/the-gold-coast-influenza-epidemic-of-1918-1919-which-killed-100000-people/|title=The Gold Coast Influenza Epidemic of 1918-1919 which killed 100,000 people|last=ghana|first=Michael Eli Dokosi-www blakkpepper com-|date=2016-11-24|website=BlakkPepper.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=PATTERSON|first=K. DAVID|date=1995|title=THE INFLUENZA EPIDEMIC OF 1918-1919 IN THE GOLD COAST|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/41406618|journal=Transactions of the Historical Society of Ghana|issue=1 (Vol. 16, no. 2)|pages=205\u2013225|issn=0855-3246}}</ref> In the local parlance it was called \"mfruensa\" by the unschooled members of the society<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Botchway|first=De-Valera NYM|url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=aPN0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA159&lpg=PA159&dq=gold+coast+influenza&source=bl&ots=5fYAv6U3Hs&sig=ACfU3U2cKO9Y43Fc0VldEATnUyjJU0JQFw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjdufyozLHoAhWqXhUIHd4ICb44ChDoATADegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=gold%20coast%20influenza&f=false|title=Africa and the First World War: Remembrance, Memories and Representations after 100 Years|last2=Kwarteng|first2=Kwame Osei|date=2018-10-26|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn=978-1-5275-2042-4|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Nature ==\nThe influenza is caused by a virus which is transmitted from one person to another. [[Virus|Viruses]] are genetically labile, hence [[Vaccine|vaccines]] are developed to cope with new strains.This was a swine flu virus with a mutation, or [[genetic recombination]], of a virulent strain with no immunity, as people had not been previously exposed to virus<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== History ==\nThere was a previous pandemic of 1889-1893 which reached the Gold coast 1891<ref>David  Scott,''Epidemic'' Disease in Ghana 1901 - 1960 (London,1965),p.187.In 1918 the Principal Medical Officer suggested that the 1891 outbreak might have been pneumonia plague (M.S.R.,1918,p.14),but this seems highly unlikey (Scott,''Epidemic'' Disease,p.188).</ref>\n\nThe governor of [[Sierra Leone]] sent a message to the governor of Ghana on 28 August 1918 of an influenza outbreak and measures are to be taken because vessels coming from [[Accra]] or Sierra Leone are infected. The message arrived late.The American vessel S.S Shonga arrived in [[Cape Coast]] on 31 August 1918.The spread of the influenza virus cause schools,Mosques and Churches<ref name=\":0\" /> to be closed down.It is recorded that an estimate of 60,000 deaths and 100,000 with total national population of 1,504,000 in 1911 [[Census|census.]]It is believed that the only measures to control was quarantine since a vaccine was introduced in 1950.\n\nThe whole colony by 1919 had 43 government  physicians ;5 of them were administrators and 5 were vacant position.<ref>Gold Coast Medical and sanitary Report for 1919 (henceforth M.S.R),P.6.</ref> The government boy's school was now the hospital with a Principal Medical officer who was given  500 pounds to care for the sick.<ref>Prin.M.O to Colonial Secretary,Accra, 17 September 1918,''ibid''</ref> After recording several fatalities they were buried in a single grave regardless of the strong african criticisms at the height of the epidemic.\n\nThe Northern western province were hard hit by the disease with 80% of the population contracting the virus.\n\n== Dates of recorded cases ==\n\nThe table indicates the city and date they recorded their first case of the virus <ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!City \n!Date recorded case\n|-\n|Accra  \n|3 september 1918\n|-\n|Koforidua\n|9 September 1918\n|-\n|Sekondi\n|18 September 1918\n|-\n|Saltpond\n|21 September 1918\n|-\n|Kumasi \n|23 September 1918\n|-\n|Winneba\n|24 September 1918\n|-\n|Tarkwa \n|25 September 1918\n|-\n|Axim\n|25 September 1918\n|-\n|Obuasi\n|1 October 1918\n|-\n|Yeji\n|8 October 1918\n|-\n|Keta\n|12 October 1918\n|-\n|Bole \n|26 October 1918\n|-\n|Wenchi, Sunyani and Kintampo\n|26 October 1918\n|-\n|Salaga \n|5 November 1918\n|-\n|Wa  \n|7 November 1918\n|-\n|Lawra\n|15 November 1918\n|-\n|Tamale\n|12 November 1918\n|-\n|Tumu\n|16 November 1918\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:Influenza pandemics]]\n[[Category:Ghana]]\n", "text_old": "An influenza epidemic in [[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold coast]] (Modern day Ghana)  in 1918-1919 killed 100,000 people or more in six months.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Patterson|first=K. David|date=October 1983|title=The Influenza Epidemic of 1918\u201319 in the Gold Coast1|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/journal-of-african-history/article/influenza-epidemic-of-191819-in-the-gold-coast1/93EFCA1CDC9FC2735A289728934E628C|journal=The Journal of African History|language=en|volume=24|issue=4|pages=485\u2013502|doi=10.1017/S0021853700028012|issn=1469-5138}}</ref> Globally 20 Million people died from the outbreak in 1918.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.blakkpepper.com/2016/11/the-gold-coast-influenza-epidemic-of-1918-1919-which-killed-100000-people/|title=The Gold Coast Influenza Epidemic of 1918-1919 which killed 100,000 people|last=ghana|first=Michael Eli Dokosi-www blakkpepper com-|date=2016-11-24|website=BlakkPepper.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=PATTERSON|first=K. DAVID|date=1995|title=THE INFLUENZA EPIDEMIC OF 1918-1919 IN THE GOLD COAST|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/41406618|journal=Transactions of the Historical Society of Ghana|issue=1 (Vol. 16, no. 2)|pages=205\u2013225|issn=0855-3246}}</ref> In the local parlance it was called \"mfruensa\" by the unschooled members of the society<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Botchway|first=De-Valera NYM|url=https://books.google.com.gh/books?id=aPN0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA159&lpg=PA159&dq=gold+coast+influenza&source=bl&ots=5fYAv6U3Hs&sig=ACfU3U2cKO9Y43Fc0VldEATnUyjJU0JQFw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjdufyozLHoAhWqXhUIHd4ICb44ChDoATADegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=gold%20coast%20influenza&f=false|title=Africa and the First World War: Remembrance, Memories and Representations after 100 Years|last2=Kwarteng|first2=Kwame Osei|date=2018-10-26|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|isbn=978-1-5275-2042-4|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Nature ==\nThe influenza is caused by a virus which is transmitted from one person to another.[[Virus|Viruses]] are gentically labile hence [[Vaccine|vacinnes]] are developed to cope with new strains.This was a swine flu virus with mutation or,[[genetic recombination]] of a virulent strain with no immunity as people had not been previously exposed to virus<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== History ==\nThere was a previous pandemic of 1889-1893 which reached the Gold coast 1891<ref>David  Scott,''Epidemic'' Disease in Ghana 1901 - 1960 (London,1965),p.187.In 1918 the Principal Medical Officer suggested that the 1891 outbreak might have been pneumonia plague (M.S.R.,1918,p.14),but this seems highly unlikey (Scott,''Epidemic'' Disease,p.188).</ref>\n\nThe governor of [[Sierra Leone]] sent a message to the governor of Ghana on 28 August 1918 of an influenza outbreak and measures are to be taken because vessels coming from [[Accra]] or Sierra Leone are infected. The message arrived late.The American vessel S.S Shonga arrived in [[Cape Coast]] on 31 August 1918.The spread of the influenza virus cause schools,Mosques and Churches<ref name=\":0\" /> to be closed down.It is recorded that an estimate of 60,000 deaths and 100,000 with total national population of 1,504,000 in 1911 [[Census|census.]]It is believed that the only measures to control was quarantine since a vaccine was introduced in 1950.\n\nThe whole colony by 1919 had 43 government  physicians ;5 of them were administrators and 5 were vacant position.<ref>Gold Coast Medical and sanitary Report for 1919 (henceforth M.S.R),P.6.</ref> The government boy's school was now the hospital with a Principal Medical officer who was given  500 pounds to care for the sick.<ref>Prin.M.O to Colonial Secretary,Accra, 17 September 1918,''ibid''</ref> After recording several fatalities they were buried in a single grave regardless of the strong african criticisms at the height of the epidemic.\n\nThe Northern western province were hard hit by the disease with 80% of the population contracting the virus.\n\n== Dates of recorded cases ==\n\nThe table indicates the city and date they recorded their first case of the virus <ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!City \n!Date recorded case\n|-\n|Accra  \n|3 september 1918\n|-\n|Koforidua\n|9 September 1918\n|-\n|Sekondi\n|18 September 1918\n|-\n|Saltpond\n|21 September 1918\n|-\n|Kumasi \n|23 September 1918\n|-\n|Winneba\n|24 September 1918\n|-\n|Tarkwa \n|25 September 1918\n|-\n|Axim\n|25 September 1918\n|-\n|Obuasi\n|1 October 1918\n|-\n|Yeji\n|8 October 1918\n|-\n|Keta\n|12 October 1918\n|-\n|Bole \n|26 October 1918\n|-\n|Wenchi, Sunyani and Kintampo\n|26 October 1918\n|-\n|Salaga \n|5 November 1918\n|-\n|Wa  \n|7 November 1918\n|-\n|Lawra\n|15 November 1918\n|-\n|Tamale\n|12 November 1918\n|-\n|Tumu\n|16 November 1918\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:Influenza pandemics]]\n[[Category:Ghana]]\n", "name_user": "Slrosen", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed some typos and misspellings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gold_Coast_Influenza_Epidemic"}
{"title_page": "Ghana Civil Service", "text_new": "The '''Ghana Civil Service''' is the single largest [[Employment|employer]] in [[Ghana]].<ref name=LAR>{{cite web|title=The Civil Service|url=http://countrystudies.us/ghana/102.htm|publisher=www.countrystudies.us|accessdate=11 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe service was established to replace the [[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]] Civil Service.<ref name=SER>{{cite web|title=Office of the head of the civil service|url=http://www.ohcs.gov.gh/|publisher=www.ohcs.gov.gh|accessdate=11 June 2011}}</ref>\nThe mission of the [[Civil service|Civil Service]], as stated in the [[Law for the Restoration of the Professional Civil Service|Civil Service Law]], 1993 PNDCL 327, \u201cis to assist the Government in the formulation and implementation of government policies for the development of the country.\u201d  The following have occurred since the inception of the service;\n\n# Before the wars of 1914 - 1918, there were many indigenous people in many senior grade positions in the civil service.\n# In 1925 \u2013 1926, '''Sir Gordon [https://www.britishempire.co.uk/biography/guggisberg.htm Guggisburg]''', the then Governor of the Gold Coast promulgated the first proposal for the development of indigenous civil service. This development was to increase the number of Africans holding high European positions and reduce the cost of employing Europeans and create a local machinery for accelerated development.\n# In 1941 a scholarship program was launched to further the Africanisation project.\n# 1948- an interim Public Service Commission was inaugurated to advice the Governor on the appointment and promotion in civil service.\n# In 1951, there was restructuring of government machinery and the establishment of statutory corporation to assume certain functions of government. \n# '''The Lidbury Committee report''' in 1951. \n# Upon attaining independence and republican status in 1957 and 1960 respectfully, various Ministries and Government Departments have been created, restructured or re-aligned to suit the needs of the times\n# In 1960, the Constituent Assembly passed the '''Civil Service Act, 1960 (CA.5).''' It provided for the following:\n#* The creation of Civil Service posts,\n#* The setting up of Ministries and Departments,\n#* The appointment and retirement of Civil Servants, and for\n#* The conditions of service, disciplinary proceedings and other matters relating to the Civil Service.\n# The Civil Service Act, 1960, was later complemented by the Civil Service (Interim) Regulations, 1960 (L1.47).\n# In 1993, '''the Civil Service Law, 1993 (PNDCL 327'''), was passed to replace the Civil Service Act, 1960 (CA.5).\n\n== Functions ==\nFor the purpose of achieving its object under the law, the Service performs the following functions-PNDC Law 32;\n\n* Initiate and formulate policy options for consideration of government;\n\n* Initiate and advise on government plans;\n* Undertake such research as may be necessary for the effective implementation of government policies;\n* Implement government policies;\n* Review government policies and plans;\n* Monitor, co-ordinate and evaluate government policies and plans;\n* Perform such functions as are incidental or conducive to the achievement of the object specified in this Law, and\n* Perform such other functions as the Executive may direct.\n\n== Mandate<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ohcs.gov.gh/welcome-office-head-civil-service|title=Welcome to The Office of Head of Civil Service {{!}} Office of the Head of Civil Service|website=www.ohcs.gov.gh|access-date=2018-11-28}}</ref> ==\nPNDC Law 327 (7) of 1993<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ilo.org/dyn/natlex/natlex4.detail?p_lang=en&p_isn=33395&p_country=GHA&p_count=114|title=Ghana - Civil Service Act (No. 327 of 1993)|website=www.ilo.org|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> mandates the office of the civil service to undertake the following:\n\n# Ensuring efficiency of the service;\n# Having charge over all Civil Servants\n# Ensuring effective implementation of government policies and plans;\n# Advising government on employment and policy formulation within the Service;\n# Advising on conduct of management audits and review, and\n# Determining and advising on manpower limits for the Service.\n\n== Vision Statement ==\nA Modernised customer-sensitive public organisation providing world-class services and policy advice.\n\n== Mission Statement ==\nThe Office of the Head of Civil Service exists to promote and ensure continuous renewal and professional development of the Human Resource of the Civil Service by ensuring that the Ministries, Departments and Agencies MDAs are optimally structured, adequately staffed with the right skills mix to provide policy advice to Ghana's political leadership to facilitate good governance and accelerated national development.\n\n== Core Values ==\nIn furtherance of its vision, mission, and corporate image, the OHCS is guided by the following core values:\n\n* Professionalism\n* Meritocracy\n* Customer sensitivity\n* Integrity\n* Accountability\n\nThe OHCS ensures that the Civil Service is staffed with competent personnel and the various Ministries, Departments and Agencies (MDAs) are well organized to provide excellent service to their diverse public.\n\n== Institutes ==\nThe Office of the Head of Civil Service currently has three(3) training institutions which perform different but complementary services to help the office achieve its objectives <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ohcs.gov.gh/resource-centres|title=Resource Centres {{!}} Office of the Head of Civil Service|website=www.ohcs.gov.gh|access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref>. These institutes include;\n\n# Civil Service Training Centre<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ohcs.gov.gh/civil-serivce-training-centre|title=Civil Serivce Training Centre {{!}} Office of the Head of Civil Service|website=www.ohcs.gov.gh|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n# Government Training School<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ohcs.gov.gh/government-training-school|title=Government Training School {{!}} Office of the Head of Civil Service|website=www.ohcs.gov.gh|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n# Institute of Technical Supervision<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/institute-of-technical-supervision-appeals-for-help.html|title=Institute of Technical Supervision appeals for help|website=Graphic Online|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Ghana topics}}\n\n{{Ministries and Agencies in Ghana}}\n\n[[Category:Government of Ghana]]\n\n\n{{Ghana-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Ghana Civil Service''' is the single largest [[Employment|employer]] in [[Ghana]].<ref name=LAR>{{cite web|title=The Civil Service|url=http://countrystudies.us/ghana/102.htm|publisher=www.countrystudies.us|accessdate=11 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe service was established to replace the [[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]] Civil Service.<ref name=SER>{{cite web|title=Office of the head of the civil service|url=http://www.ohcs.gov.gh/|publisher=www.ohcs.gov.gh|accessdate=11 June 2011}}</ref>\nThe mission of the [[Civil service|Civil Service]], as stated in the [[Law for the Restoration of the Professional Civil Service|Civil Service Law]], 1993 PNDCL 327, \u201cis to assist the Government in the formulation and implementation of government policies for the development of the country.\u201d  The following have occurred since the inception of the service;\n\n# Before the wars of 1914 - 1918, there were many indigenous people in many senior grade positions in the civil service.\n# In 1925 \u2013 1926, '''Sir Gordon [https://www.britishempire.co.uk/biography/guggisberg.htm Guggisburg]''', the then Governor of the Gold Coast promulgated the first proposal for the development of indigenous civil service. This development was to increase the number of Africans holding high European positions and reduce the cost of employing Europeans and create a local machinery for accelerated development.\n# In 1941 a scholarship program was launched to further the Africanisation project.\n# 1948- an interim Public Service Commission was inaugurated to advice the Governor on the appointment and promotion in civil service.\n# In 1951, there was restructuring of government machinery and the establishment of statutory corporation to assume certain functions of government. \n# '''The Lidbury Committee report''' in 1951. \n# Upon attaining independence and republican status in 1957 and 1960 respectfully, various Ministries and Government Departments have been created, restructured or re-aligned to suit the needs of the times\n# In 1960, the Constituent Assembly passed the '''Civil Service Act, 1960 (CA.5).''' It provided for the following:\n#* The creation of Civil Service posts,\n#* The setting up of Ministries and Departments,\n#* The appointment and retirement of Civil Servants, and for\n#* The conditions of service, disciplinary proceedings and other matters relating to the Civil Service.\n# The Civil Service Act, 1960, was later complemented by the Civil Service (Interim) Regulations, 1960 (L1.47).\n# In 1993, '''the Civil Service Law, 1993 (PNDCL 327'''), was passed to replace the Civil Service Act, 1960 (CA.5).\n\n== Functions ==\nFor the purpose of achieving its object under the law, the Service performs the following functions-PNDC Law 32;\n\n* Initiate and formulate policy options for consideration of government;\n\n* Initiate and advise on government plans;\n* Undertake such research as may be necessary for the effective implementation of government policies;\n* Implement government policies;\n* Review government policies and plans;\n* Monitor, co-ordinate and evaluate government policies and plans;\n* Perform such functions as are incidental or conducive to the achievement of the object specified in this Law, and\n* Perform such other functions as the Executive may direct.\n\n== Mandate<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ohcs.gov.gh/welcome-office-head-civil-service|title=Welcome to The Office of Head of Civil Service {{!}} Office of the Head of Civil Service|website=www.ohcs.gov.gh|access-date=2018-11-28}}</ref> ==\nPNDC Law 327 (7) of 1993<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ilo.org/dyn/natlex/natlex4.detail?p_lang=en&p_isn=33395&p_country=GHA&p_count=114|title=Ghana - Civil Service Act (No. 327 of 1993)|website=www.ilo.org|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref> mandates the office of the civil service to undertake the following:\n\n# Ensuring efficiency of the service;\n# Having charge over all Civil Servants\n# Ensuring effective implementation of government policies and plans;\n# Advising government on employment and policy formulation within the Service;\n# Advising on conduct of management audits and review, and\n# Determining and advising on manpower limits for the Service.\n\n== Vision Statement ==\nA Modernised customer-sensitive public organisation providing world-class services and policy advice.\n\n== Mission Statement ==\nThe Office of the Head of Civil Service exists to promote and ensure continuous renewal and professional development of the Human Resource of the Civil Service by ensuring that the Ministries, Departments and Agencies MDAs are optimally structured, adequately staffed with the right skills mix to provide policy advice to Ghana\u2019s political leadership to facilitate good governance and accelerated national development.\n\n== Core Values ==\nIn furtherance of its vision, mission, and corporate image, the OHCS is guided by the following core values:\n\n* Professionalism\n* Meritocracy\n* Customer sensitivity\n* Integrity\n* Accountability\n\nThe OHCS ensures that the Civil Service is staffed with competent personnel and the various Ministries, Departments and Agencies (MDAs) are well organized to provide excellent service to their diverse public.\n\n== Institutes ==\nThe Office of the Head of Civil Service currently has three(3) training institutions which perform different but complementary services to help the office achieve its objectives <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ohcs.gov.gh/resource-centres|title=Resource Centres {{!}} Office of the Head of Civil Service|website=www.ohcs.gov.gh|access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref>. These institutes include;\n\n# Civil Service Training Centre<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ohcs.gov.gh/civil-serivce-training-centre|title=Civil Serivce Training Centre {{!}} Office of the Head of Civil Service|website=www.ohcs.gov.gh|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n# Government Training School<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ohcs.gov.gh/government-training-school|title=Government Training School {{!}} Office of the Head of Civil Service|website=www.ohcs.gov.gh|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n# Institute of Technical Supervision<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.graphic.com.gh/news/general-news/institute-of-technical-supervision-appeals-for-help.html|title=Institute of Technical Supervision appeals for help|website=Graphic Online|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Ghana topics}}\n\n{{Ministries and Agencies in Ghana}}\n\n[[Category:Government of Ghana]]\n\n\n{{Ghana-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMission Statement:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghana_Civil_Service"}
